title: For Sale:  Nazi marked Collector ammo for the Austrian Steyr M95 - Six (6) boxes
postcontent:
Six original boxes of Nazi produced and marked Steyr M95 collector ammo. 
Each box contains two (2) original charger clips (it IS a 'clip' in this case, similar to the Garand in concept) and the original load of five (5) rounds of ammunition in each of the two (2) charger clips, within each box.

Each original box and the head-stamp on all the ammunition has a "nazi eagle over swastika" waffenampt, and is marked manufactured in August 1938.. Austria had become part of Nazi Germany five months earlier, in March of 1938.

The maker markings on the 12 ammo clips inside these boxes are mostly Nazi waffenampts with the "eagle over swastika",
 but there is at least one "Federal Republic of Austria Double-Eagle" in one pack, along with several 'Georg Roth. Vienna, Austria.' "GR" marked clips, and there is at least one 'Manfred Weiss Works (Weiss Manfréd Muvek). Csepel (later Budapest), Hungary' "W in a circle" marked clip. The entire lot includes a total of 60 rounds of nazi-marked ammunition in their 12 original loading clips and in the original packaging. 

(Please note!- this variety of 8mm ammunition is specifically used in a series of Austrian or Austro-Hungarian rifles and is NOT designed or suitable for the German K98 WW2 military rifle, which uses a slightly different cartridge. 
This ammunition was produced during WW2 after Austria became part of Nazi Germany, and the Nazis continued to use and issue the existing stock of former Austro-Hungarian military rifles as police or second-line weapons)

I will sell each box for $20 each, or you can take the entire lot for $90 cash. 
I am not going to ship ammo since it can only go via UPS (Cannot be sent USPS) and I do not want to deal with the UPS requirements, so you will need to meet FTF to pick up the ammunition.  Buyer must have valid FOID to take possession of any ammo. thanks.

The TSD-MAG15 is a hybrid magazine that combines the best features of polymer and steel magazine designs. Unlike many polymer-only feed lips, the hardened steel feed lips won’t bend, break or deform due to rough handling or long term storage. The lip on the magazine extends from front to back, from the top of the lips, down to the top of the mag latch area, which allows the magazine to sit on the catch with metal to metal contact, instead of the metal of the mag catch possibly gouging the polymer magazine body and causing feed issues.    
An aggressive surface texture has been applied to the polymer body to improve gripping and retrieval from pouches. The floor plate is also slimmer than other polymer magazines, maintaining a slimmer outer profile, and making it easier to use in double mag pouches. Disassembly is quite simple, using only a single round of ammo to depress the locking plate, and slide the floor plate to the rear, off the magazine body.
